</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCC6A73FF889C9A1A3AB069" pageId="55" pageNumber="813" type="activity">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCC6A73FF889C9A1A3AB069" blockId="55.[116,1325,1611,3301]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFCC6A73FF889C9A1F5FB1D6" bold="true" box="[116,351,2755,2788]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Peters’s Pipistrelle is nocturnal. In Borneo (Crocker Range) and the 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFCC6A73FF8B9CB21F14B03E" box="[119,276,2795,2828]" name="Philippines" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">Philippines</collectingCountry>
it was found roosting under the eaves of houses. Another specimen was captured on Mount Amuyao (LLuzon) in an area dominated by old-growth mossy forest. Peters’s Pipistrelles have been seen flying into wooden buildings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCC6A73FF8A9D381A21B0B0" box="[118,1057,2913,2946]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCC6A73FF8A9D381A21B0B0" blockId="55.[116,1325,1611,3301]" box="[118,1057,2913,2946]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFCC6A73FF8A9D381D32B0B0" bold="true" box="[118,818,2913,2946]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFCC6A73FF8B9DD41D60B775" pageId="55" pageNumber="813" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFCC6A73FF8B9DD41D60B775" blockId="55.[116,1325,1611,3301]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFCC6A73FF8B9DD41FD1B098" bold="true" box="[119,465,2957,2986]" pageId="55" pageNumber="813">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List (as 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFCC6A73FB499DD41EF9B0E2" baseAuthorityName="A. Meyer" baseAuthorityYear="1899" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Falsistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="813" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="petersi">Falsistrellus petersi</taxonomicName>
), as there are only a few scattered records over a wide area. It may be declining because of widespread habitat loss in the region, but precise habitat requirements are not known. The species occurs in Kubah National Park. Further studies are needed into its distribution, abundance, ecology, and threats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
